{"title_page": "John Ryder (boxer)", "text_new": "{{short description|English boxer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = John Ryder\n| image = John Ryder - O2 Arena 2015-05-30.jpg\n| caption = Ryder in 2015\n| nickname = The Gorilla\n| weight = {{plainlist|\n*[[Middleweight]]\n*[[Super-middleweight]]\n}}\n| height = 5 ft 9 in\n| reach = 72 in\n| nationality = British\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|7|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Islington]], [[London]], England\n| style = [[Southpaw stance|Southpaw]]\n| total = 33\n| wins = 28\n| KO = 16\n| losses = 5\n| draws = \n| no contests = \n}}\n\n'''John Ryder'''  (born 19 July 1988) is a British [[professional boxer]] who held the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[interim championship|interim]] [[super-middleweight]] title from May to November 2019. At regional level he has challenged twice for the [[British Boxing Board of Control|British]] [[middleweight]] title in 2013 and 2015, and once for the British super-middleweight title in 2017.\n\n==Amateur career==\nAs an [[amateur boxing|amateur]], Ryder fought for Angel Amateur Boxing Club in his birthplace of [[Islington]], winning 30 fights out of 35.<ref>[http://www.boxingnews24.com/2010/08/john-ryder-set-to-go-pro/ \"John Ryder set to go pro\"]. Boxing News 24. 24 August 2010. Retrieved 18 March 2016.</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nRyder turned professional on 10 September 2010, scoring a first-round [[technical knockout|stoppage]] against Ben Deghani. Having won his first fifteen fights, Ryder faced fellow undefeated prospect [[Billy Joe Saunders]] for his [[British Boxing Board of Control|British]] and [[Commonwealth Boxing Council|Commonwealth]] [[middleweight]] titles on 21 September 2013, losing a close [[unanimous decision]] (UD) with scores of 115\u2013113, 115\u2013113 and 115\u2013114 for Saunders.<ref>https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1782841</ref> Ryder won his first regional championship\u2014the vacant [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] Inter-Continental middleweight title\u2014on 11 October 2014, stopping Theophilus Tetteh in five rounds.<ref>Brennan, Rob (29 January 2015). [http://www.islingtongazette.co.uk/sport/boxing/islington_middleweight_john_ryder_wants_a_proper_fight_at_the_o2_arena_1_3934118 \"Islington middleweight John Ryder wants a proper fight at the O2 Arena\"]. ''[[Islington Gazette]]''. [[Archant]]. Retrieved 11 August 2015.</ref> He defended this title once, against Billi Facundo Godoy with a tenth-round stoppage.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/9693480/fight-night-live-john-wayne-hibbert-and-john-ryder-earned-stoppage-victories \"John Wayne Hibbert and John Ryder earn stoppage victories at the O2 Arena\"]. ''[[Sky Sports]]''. [[Sky (United Kingdom)|Sky]]. 1 February 2015. Retrieved 11 August 2015.</ref>\n\nAfter Saunders vacated the British middleweight title, a bout was held between top contenders Ryder and [[Nick Blackwell]] on 30 May 2015. Ryder was widely ahead on the scorecards when he was stopped on his feet by Blackwell in the seventh round.<ref>[http://www1.skysports.com/boxing/news/20876/9870349/nick-blackwell-wins-british-middleweight-title-with-stoppage-victory-over-john-ryder \"Nick Blackwell wins British middleweight title with stoppage victory over John Ryder\"]. ''[[Sky Sports]]''. [[Sky (United Kingdom)|Sky]]. 30 May 2015. Retrieved 11 August 2015.</ref> Ryder bounced back on 30 January 2016, winning his second regional championship\u2014the vacant [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] International middleweight title\u2014with a UD over [[Sergey Khomitsky]].<ref>https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10149961/john-ryder</ref>\n\nRyder defended his WBA International middleweight title against [[Jack Arnfield]] on 24 September 2016, losing to a unanimous decision over twelve rounds.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gilbert |first1=Peter |title=Jack Arnfield upsets John Ryder with points victory |url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10592508/jack-arnfield-upsets-john-ryder-with-points-victory |website=Sky Sports |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=25 September 2016}}</ref> Ryder rebounded in his next fight, defeating [[Adam Etches]] by unanimous decision to win the IBF international super middleweight title.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Assuncao |first1=Miguel |title=John Ryder Captures IBF Regional Belt, Defeats Adam Etches |url=https://www.boxingscene.com/john-ryder-captures-ibf-regional-belt-defeats-adam-etches--113314 |website=BoxingScene |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=4 February 2017}}</ref> On 22 April 2017, Ryder moved up to [[super-middleweight]] to face [[Rocky Fielding]] for the British title but lost to a [[split decision]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prentice |first1=David |title=Rocky Fielding exorcises demons after attritional scrap with John Ryder |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/boxing/rocky-fielding-exorcises-demons-after-12932123 |website=Liverpool Echo |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=23 April 2017}}</ref> On the Canelo vs Jacobs card in Las Vegas in May 2019, Ryder beat Bilal Akkawy by technical knockout in the third round to win the vacant interim WBA super-middleweight title and put himself in line to challenge [[Callum Smith]] for the WBA super-middleweight title.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gilbert |first1=Peter |title=Canelo vs Jacobs: John Ryder preserves mandatory status to Calllum Smith's WBA 'Super' title |url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11711843/canelo-vs-jacobs-john-ryder-secures-mandatory-status-to-calllum-smiths-wba-super-title |website=Sky Sports |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=5 May 2019}}</ref> Following the successful defeat of Akkawy, Ryder fought [[Callum Smith]] for the super-middleweight title in November 2019, losing a competitive bout by unanimous decision.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gilbert |first1=Peter |title=Smith vs Ryder: Callum Smith defeats John Ryder to retain WBA crown in homecoming fight |url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11868738/smith-vs-ryder-callum-smith-defeats-john-ryder-to-retain-wba-crown-in-homecoming-fight |website=Sky Sports |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=16 \n|ko-losses=1\n|dec-wins=11\n|dec-losses=4\n|dq-wins=1\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|33\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|28\u20135\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Callum Smith]]\n|UD\n|12\n|23 Nov 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|M&S Bank Arena, Liverpool, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|For [[list of WBA world champions#Super middleweight|WBA (Super)]] and [[list of The Ring world champions#Super middleweight|''The Ring'' super-middleweight titles]]}}\n|-\n|32\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|28\u20134\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|AUS}} Bilal Akkawy\n|TKO\n|3 (12), {{small|2:12}}\n|4 May 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[T-Mobile Arena]], [[Paradise, Nevada]], US}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won vacant WBA [[Interim champion|interim]] super-middleweight title}}\n|-\n|31\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|27\u20134\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Andrey Sirotkin]]\n|KO\n|7 (12), {{small|2:54}}\n|27 Oct 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Copper Box Arena, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|30\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|26\u20134\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Jamie Cox (boxer)|Jamie Cox]]\n|KO\n|2 (12), {{small|0:50}}\n|5 May 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|The O2 Arena, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|29\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|25\u20134\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Patrick Nielsen]]\n|KO\n|5 (10), {{small|3:00}}\n|14 Oct 2017\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[The SSE Arena Wembley]], London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|28\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|24\u20134\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Rocky Fielding]]\n|SD\n|12\n|22 Apr 2017\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Echo Arena, Liverpool, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|For vacant [[list of British super-middleweight boxing champions|British super-middleweight title]]}}\n|-\n|27\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|24\u20133\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Adam Etches]]\n|UD\n|12\n|4 Feb 2017\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|London Olympia, London, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won vacant [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] International [[super-middleweight]] title}}\n|-\n|26\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|23\u20133\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Jack Arnfield]]\n|UD\n|12\n|24 Sep 2016\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Manchester Arena]], [[Manchester]], England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Lost WBA International middleweight title}}\n|-\n|25\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|23\u20132\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|POL}} [[Robert Talarek]]\n|PTS\n|6\n|28 May 2016\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[The SSE Hydro]], [[Glasgow]], Scotland}}\n|\n|-\n|24\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|22\u20132\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Sergey Khomitsky]]\n|UD\n|12\n|30 Jan 2016\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Copper Box Arena, London, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won vacant [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] International middleweight title}}\n|-\n|23\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|21\u20132\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Adam Jones\n|PTS\n|6\n|10 Oct 2015\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|York Hall, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|22\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|20\u20132\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Nick Blackwell]]\n|TKO\n|7 (12), {{small|2:36}}\n|30 May 2015\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|The O2 Arena, London, Engla