}\n|5 Apr 2014\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|York Hall, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|17\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|16-1\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|GEO}} Giorgi Kandelaki\n|PTS\n|6\n|15 Mar 2014\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Echo Arena Liverpool|Echo Arena]], [[Liverpool]], England}}\n|\n|-\n|16\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|15\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Billy Joe Saunders]]\n|UD\n|12\n|21 Sep 2013\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Copper Box Arena]], London, England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|For [[list of British middleweight boxing champions|British]] and [[list of Commonwealth Boxing Council champions#Middleweight|Commonwealth middleweight titles]]}}\n|-\n|15\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|15\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|FRA}} Yoann Bloyer\n|TKO\n|2 (6), {{small|0:45}}\n|13 Jul 2013\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Craven Park, Hull|Craven Park]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], England}}\n|\n|-\n|14\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|14\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|ZIM}} Farai Musiyiwa\n|PTS\n|8\n|9 Mar 2013\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Wembley Arena, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|13\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|13\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Eamonn O'Kane]]\n|TKO\n|8 (10), {{small|1:33}}\n|8 Dec 2012\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|London Olympia, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|12\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|12\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|HUN}} Sandor Micsko\n|TKO\n|2 (8), {{small|2:52}}\n|8 Sep 2012\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Alexandra Palace]], London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|11\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|11\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Luke Robinson\n|PTS\n|8\n|26 May 2012\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Capital FM Arena Nottingham|Nottingham Arena]], [[Nottingham]], England}}\n|\n|-\n|10\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|10\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Alistair Warren\n|PTS\n|8\n|17 Mar 2012\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Motorpoint Arena Sheffield|Motorpoint Arena]], [[Sheffield]], England}}\n|\n|-\n|9\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|9\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|POL}} Mariusz Biskupski\n|TKO\n|2 (8), {{small|2:21}}\n|28 Jan 2012\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|York Hall, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|8\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|8\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|CRO}} Zoran Cvek\n|TKO\n|3 (10), {{small|2:49}}\n|3 Dec 2011\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|Prince Regent Hotel, [[Chigwell]], England}}\n|\n|-\n|7\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|7\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Luke Osman\n|TKO\n|2 (6), {{small|2:13}}\n|9 Nov 2011\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|York Hall, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|6\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|6\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Danny Brown\n|TKO\n|1 (4), {{small|0:37}}\n|8 Oct 2011\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|York Hall, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|5\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|5\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Lee Noble\n|PTS\n|6\n|30 Apr 2011\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[London Olympia]], London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|4\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|4\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Dalton Miller\n|RTD\n|2 (4), {{small|3:00}}\n|26 Mar 2011\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|City Limits Pavilion, London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|3\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|3\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Lewis Byrne\n|PTS\n|4\n|19 Feb 2011\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[Wembley Arena]], London, England}}\n|\n|-\n|2\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|2\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} Sabie Montieth\n|DQ\n|1 (4), {{small|1:00}}\n|4 Dec 2010\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|York Hall, [[London]], England}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Montieth disqualified for headbutting}}\n|-\n|1\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|1\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|IRN}} Ben Deghani\n|TKO\n|1 (4), {{small|1:30}}\n|10 Sep 2010\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} {{small|[[York Hall]], [[London]], England}}\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Boxrec|id=545557}}\n*[http://www.matchroomboxing.com/boxers/john-ryder/ John Ryder profile] at [[Matchroom Boxing]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{s-text|style=background:#C1D8FF; font-weight: bold;|text=Regional boxing titles}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-vac|last=[[Matt Korobov]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] Inter-Continental<br>[[middleweight]] champion\n|years=11 October 2014 \u2013 29 May 2015<br>Vacated}}\n{{s-vac|next=[[Tommy Langford]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-vac|last=[[Tureano Johnson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[World Boxing Association|WBA]] International<br>middleweight champion\n|years=30 January 2016 \u2013 24 September 2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jack Arnfield]]}}\n{{s-vac|last=[[Stanislav Kashtanov]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[IBF]] International super-middleweight champion\n|years=4 February 2017 \u2013 October 2017<br>Vacated}}\n{{s-vac|next=Ronny Landaeta}}\n{{s-text|style=background:#C1D8FF; font-weight: bold;|text=World boxing titles}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-vac|last=[[Vincent Feigenbutz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of WBA world champions#Super middleweight|WBA super-middleweight champion]]<br>[[Interim title]]\n|years=5 May \u2013 23 November 2019<br>Lost bid for [[WBA (Super)|Super title]]}}\n{{s-vac}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ryder, John}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Middleweight boxers]]\n[[Category:English male boxers]]\n[[Category:People from Islington (district)]]\n[[Category:Boxers from Greater London]]\n[[Category:Super-middleweight boxers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProfessional career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: an unanimous \u2192 a unanimous", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Ryder_(boxer)"}
{"title_page": "Una Troy", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish novelist}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = Una Troy\n| birth_date         = 21 May 1910 (some sources give 1913)\n| birth_place        = Fermoy, County Cork\n| death_date         = 27 September 1993\n| death_place        = Bonmahon\n| nationality        = Irish\n| occupation         = Novelist and playwright\n| relatives          = [[Se\u00e1n Keating]] (brother-in-law)\n}}\n\n'''Una Troy Walsh''' (21 May 1910 \u2013 27 September 1993) was an [[List of Irish novelists|Irish novelist]] and playwright who wrote under the names '''Elizabeth Connor''' and '''Una Troy'''.\n\n== Early life ==\nTroy was born in [[Fermoy]], [[County Cork]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Owen|first=Emma Mae|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662382/both-tears-and-laughter-found-in-we/|title=Both Tears and Laughter Found in 'We Are Seven'|date=1957-03-24|work=The Jackson Sun|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=29|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> the daughter of John S. Troy and Brigid Agnes Hayes. Her father was a lawyer and a judge. Her sister Gr\u00e1inne (or Grania, 1913-1970) was a musician, and her sister Shevaun (1923-1993) was a poet.<ref name=\":0\">Butler, Ann M. ''[https://www.nli.ie/pdfs/mss%20lists/troyu.pdf Collection List for Una Troy Papers]'', National Library of Ireland.</ref> She was educated at the Loreto Convent in [[Rathfarnham]], Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803105904457|title=Una Troy|last=|first=|date=|website=The Concise Oxford Companion to Irish Literature|language=en|doi=10.1093/oi/authority.20110803105904457|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Before and during World War II ===\nWriting under the pen name of \"Elizabeth Connor\",<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Walsh|first=I.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BiMqiOVPp8EC&ppis=_e&lpg=PA183&ots=Sxge1ec1F5&dq=Una%20Troy&pg=PA74#v=onepage&q=Una%20Troy&f=false|title=Experimental Irish Theatre: After W.B. Yeats|date=2012-03-13|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-00136-8|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=O'Reilly|first=Terence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E-sl4wW6KwcC&ppis=_e&lpg=PA220&ots=QV_5Sb-zjT&dq=%22Elizabeth%20Connor%22%20Rebel%20Heart&pg=PA220#v=onepage&q=%22Elizabeth%20Connor%22%20Rebel%20Heart&f=false|title=Rebel Heart: George Lennon : Flying Column Commander|date=2009|publisher=Mercier Press Ltd|year=|isbn=978-1-85635-649-7|location=|pages=220-224|language=en}}</ref> she began her career in 1936 with the publication of the novel ''Mount Prospect'', which was banned in the [[Irish Free State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucd.ie/scholarcast/transcripts/four_nations_feminism.pdf|title= Four Nations Feminism: Una Troy and Menna Gallie|last= Connolly|first=Claire|date=Spring 2010|publisher=UCDscholarcast|pages=3|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref> Adapted as a play, it garnered the [[Shaw Prize]] for new playwrights and was performed on the [[Abbey Theatre, Dublin|Abbey]] stage in 1940. Two subsequent plays by Troy ''Swans and Geese'' and ''An Apple a Day,'' were also performed at the Abbey in the early 1940s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Leland|first=Mary|title=The lie of the land: journeys through literary Cork |publisher=Cork University Press|year=1999|pages=161|isbn=978-1-85918-231-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PL1YhI3Rp1cC&pg=PA161&dq=%22Una+Troy%22+born+fermoy&hl=en&sa=X&ei=rKzqTrzmKZO7hAekqKydCA&sqi=2&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Una%20Troy%22%20born%20fermoy&f=false|accessdate=2011-12-16}}</ref><ref>[http://www.irishplayography.com/person.aspx?personid=39303 \"People: Elizabeth Connor\"] ''Irish Playography''.</ref> \n\nIn 1938, ''Dead Star's Light'' was published. The protagonist, John Davern, was based on the character of IRA revolutionary idealist [[George Lennon]] of West [[County Waterford|Waterford]]. While not banned, it did elicit censure from Troy's parish priest in Clonmel.<ref name=\":2\" /> ''Dead Star's Light'' was performed on the Abbey stage in 1947 as ''The Dark Road''.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== After World War II ===\nIn the post-World War II period Troy wrote more fifteen novels, under her own name. ''Miss Maggie and the Doctor'' (1958) was considered \"as Irish as the shamrock\" with \"a unique exuberance and charm\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Owen|first=Emma Mae|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662148/una-troys-gay-novels-continue-to-charm/|title=Una Troy's Gay Novels Continue to Charm Readers|date=1958-08-17|work=The Jackson Sun|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=11|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' described her 1959 novel ''The Other End of the Bridge'' as \"Funny in its presentation but not in its intent,\" adding that Troy \"points up universal problems in microcosm, and stirs its Irish stew with a sturdy ladle.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/a/una-troy-4/the-other-end-of-the-bridge/|title=The Other End of the Bridge|last=|first=|date=4 January 1960|website=Kirkus Reviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nTroy's 1955 novel, ''We Are Seven'', was adapted as a film, ''She Didn't Say No!'' (1958), for which she was the co-writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ifi.ie/film/she-didnt-say-no-3/|title=She Didn't Say No|website=Irish Film Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Because of its portrayal of illegitimacy, the film was not released in Ireland until it was shown in 2001 at the [[Irish Film Archive]]. It was also shown at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York in 2005, as part of an international film preservation festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=1247&tpl=archnews&force=1|title=MOMA To Screen Restored 'She Didn\u2019t Say No!'|last=|first=|date=1 April 2005|website=The Irish Film & Television Network|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n* ''Mount Prospect'' (also known as ''No House of Peace'', 1936)\n* ''Dead Star's Light'' (1938)\n* ''We Are Seven'' (1955)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Troy|first=Una|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/We_are_Seven.html?id=NoiCOwAACAAJ|title=We are Seven|date=1990|publisher=Chivers|isbn=978-0-86220-607-9|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Miss Maggie'' ''and the Doctor'' (also known as ''Maggie'', 1958)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Troy|first=Una|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XLA_HaWQ-FAC&newbks=0&hl=en|title=Miss Maggie and the Doctor|date=1958|publisher=Dutton|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/06/29/110080354.html|title=Dr. Bill's Housekeeper|last=Cobb|first=Jane|date=29 June 1958|website=New York Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n* ''The Workhouse Graces'' (also known as ''The Graces of Ballykeen,'' 1959)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Minick|first=Elaine I.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662552/sisters-in-paupers-home-find-riches-in/|title=Sisters in Paupers' Home Find Riches in Friendship|date=1960-01-10|work=Chattanooga Daily Times|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=16|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* ''The Other End of the Bridge'' (1960)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Troy|first=Una|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XrJSxAEACAAJ&newbks=0&hl=en|title=The Other End of the Bridge|date=1960|publisher=Heinemann|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Johnson|first=C. W.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662718/irish-feuding-becomes-frolicc-w/|title=Irish Feuding Becomes Frolic|date=1961-01-08|work=Springfield Leader and Press|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=27|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* ''Esmond'' (1962)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burns|first=G. Frank|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662804/trigamyg-frank-burns/|title=Trigamy|date=1962-07-22|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=32|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* ''The Brimstone Halo'' (also known as ''The Prodigal Father'', 1965)<ref>{{Cite news|last=B. H. H.|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662647/prodigal-father-returns-to-family-he/|title='Prodigal Father' Returns to Family He Left Behind|date=1965-03-21|work=The Anniston Star|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=16|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* ''The Benefactors'' (1969)\n* ''The Castle Nobody Wanted'' (1970)\n* ''Tiger Puss'' (1970)\n* ''Doctor Go Home'' (1973)\n* ''Out of Everywhere'' (1976)\n* ''Caught in the Furze'' (1977)\n* ''A Sack of Gold'' (1979)\n* ''So True a Fool'' (1981)\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1931, Una Troy married Joseph C. Walsh of [[Bunmahon|Bonmahon]], who served as physician to the [[Irish Republican Army (1922\u20131969)|Irish Republican Army]] (IRA),<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Reilly|first=Terence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E-sl4wW6KwcC&pg=PA220&dq=%22Una+Troy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=R6rqTv7GIdSXhQeirbXBCA&ved=0CFAQ6AEwBzgU#v=onepage&q=%22Una%20Troy%22&f=false|title=Rebel Heart: George Lennon: Flying Column Commander|publisher=Mercier Press Ltd|year=2009|isbn=978-1-85635-649-7|pages=220|accessdate=2011-12-16}}</ref> and later as a coroner. Her sister-in-law [[May Keating|May Walsh]] was married to Irish artist [[Se\u00e1n Keating]]. The couple lived in [[Clonmel]] for most of their lives together, and had a daughter, Janet (1932-2002). Una Troy was widowed when Dr. Walsh died in 1969, and she died in 1993 in Bonmahon, County Waterford.<ref name=\":1\" /> Many of her papers are in the collection of the [[National Library of Ireland]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.unatroy.info Una Troy], a website run by Troy biographer and archivist Ann M. Butler.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0873914}}\n*Claire Connolly, \"Scholarcast 19: Four Nations Feminism: Una Troy and [[Menna Gallie]]\", an audio program from [[University College Dublin]].\n*[https://www.rte.ie/archives/2017/0228/856053-times-changing-in-clonmel/ \"Clonmel at Crossroads of Change\"] (16 March 1967), an episode of the RT\u00c9 series ''Discovery,'' featuring Una Troy.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Troy, Una}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:People from County Cork]]\n[[Category:People from County Waterford]]\n[[Category:Irish women novelists]]\n[[Category:Irish women dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish novelist}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = Una Troy\n| birth_date         = 21 May 1910 (some sources give 1913)\n| birth_place        = Fermoy, County Cork\n| death_date         = 27 September 1993\n| death_place        = Bonmahon\n| nationality        = Irish\n| occupation         = Novelist and playwright\n| relatives          = [[Se\u00e1n Keating]] (brother-in-law)\n}}\n\n'''Una Troy Walsh''' (21 May 1910 \u2013 27 September 1993) was an [[List of Irish novelists|Irish novelist]] and playwright who wrote under the names '''Elizabeth Connor''' and '''Una Troy'''.\n\n== Early life ==\nTroy was born in [[Fermoy]], [[County Cork]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Owen|first=Emma Mae|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662382/both-tears-and-laughter-found-in-we/|title=Both Tears and Laughter Found in 'We Are Seven'|date=1957-03-24|work=The Jackson Sun|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=29|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> the daughter of John S. Troy and Brigid Agnes Hayes. Her father was a lawyer and a judge. Her sister Gr\u00e1inne (or Grania, 1913-1970) was a musician, and her sister Shevaun (1923-1993) was a poet.<ref name=\":0\">Butler, Ann M. ''[https://www.nli.ie/pdfs/mss%20lists/troyu.pdf Collection List for Una Troy Papers]'', National Library of Ireland.</ref> She was educated at the Loreto Convent in [[Rathfarnham]], Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803105904457|title=Una Troy|last=|first=|date=|website=The Concise Oxford Companion to Irish Literature|language=en|doi=10.1093/oi/authority.20110803105904457|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Before and during World War II ===\nWriting under the pen name of \"Elizabeth Connor\",<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Walsh|first=I.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BiMqiOVPp8EC&ppis=_e&lpg=PA183&ots=Sxge1ec1F5&dq=Una%20Troy&pg=PA74#v=onepage&q=Una%20Troy&f=false|title=Experimental Irish Theatre: After W.B. Yeats|date=2012-03-13|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-00136-8|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=O'Reilly|first=Terence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E-sl4wW6KwcC&ppis=_e&lpg=PA220&ots=QV_5Sb-zjT&dq=%22Elizabeth%20Connor%22%20Rebel%20Heart&pg=PA220#v=onepage&q=%22Elizabeth%20Connor%22%20Rebel%20Heart&f=false|title=Rebel Heart: George Lennon : Flying Column Commander|date=2009|publisher=Mercier Press Ltd|year=|isbn=978-1-85635-649-7|location=|pages=220-224|language=en}}</ref> she began her career in 1936 with the publication of the novel ''Mount Prospect'', which was banned in the [[Irish Free State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucd.ie/scholarcast/transcripts/four_nations_feminism.pdf|title= Four Nations Feminism: Una Troy and Menna Gallie|last= Connolly|first=Claire|date=Spring 2010|publisher=UCDscholarcast|pages=3|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref> Adapted as a play, it garnered the [[Shaw Prize]] for new playwrights and was performed on the [[Abbey Theatre, Dublin|Abbey]] stage in 1940. Two subsequent plays by Troy ''Swans and Geese'' and ''An Apple a Day,'' were also performed at the Abbey in the early 1940s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Leland|first=Mary|title=The lie of the land: journeys through literary Cork |publisher=Cork University Press|year=1999|pages=161|isbn=978-1-85918-231-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PL1YhI3Rp1cC&pg=PA161&dq=%22Una+Troy%22+born+fermoy&hl=en&sa=X&ei=rKzqTrzmKZO7hAekqKydCA&sqi=2&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Una%20Troy%22%20born%20fermoy&f=false|accessdate=2011-12-16}}</ref><ref>[http://www.irishplayography.com/person.aspx?personid=39303 \"People: Elizabeth Connor\"] ''Irish Playography''.</ref> \n\nIn 1938, ''Dead Star's Light'' was published. The protagonist, John Davern, was based on the character of IRA revolutionary idealist [[George Lennon]] of West [[County Waterford|Waterford]]. While not banned, it did elicit censure from Troy's parish priest in Clonmel.<ref name=\":2\" /> ''Dead Star's Light'' was performed on the Abbey stage in 1947 as ''The Dark Road''.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== After World War II ===\nIn the post-World War II period Troy wrote more fifteen novels, under her own name. ''Miss Maggie and the Doctor'' (1958) was considered \"as Irish as the shamrock\" with \"a unique exuberance and charm\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Owen|first=Emma Mae|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662148/una-troys-gay-novels-continue-to-charm/|title=Una Troy's Gay Novels Continue to Charm Readers|date=1958-08-17|work=The Jackson Sun|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=11|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' described her 1959 novel ''The Other End of the Bridge'' as \"Funny in its presentation but not in its intent,\" adding that Troy \"points up universal problems in microcosm, and stirs its Irish stew with a sturdy ladle.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/a/una-troy-4/the-other-end-of-the-bridge/|title=The Other End of the Bridge|last=|first=|date=4 January 1960|website=Kirkus Reviews|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nTroy's 1955 novel, ''We Are Seven'', was adapted as a film, ''She Didn't Say No!'' (1958), for which she was the co-writer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ifi.ie/film/she-didnt-say-no-3/|title=She Didn't Say No|website=Irish Film Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Because of its portrayal of illegitimacy, the film was not released in Ireland until it was shown in 2001 at the [[Irish Film Archive]]. It was also shown at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York in 2005, as part of an international film preservation festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=1247&tpl=archnews&force=1|title=MOMA To Screen Restored 'She Didn\u2019t Say No!'|last=|first=|date=1 April 2005|website=The Irish Film & Television Network|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n* ''Mount Prospect'' (also known as ''No House of Peace'', 1936)\n* ''Dead Star's Light'' (1938)\n* ''We Are Seven'' (1955)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Troy|first=Una|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/We_are_Seven.html?id=NoiCOwAACAAJ|title=We are Seven|date=1990|publisher=Chivers|isbn=978-0-86220-607-9|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Miss Maggie'' ''and the Doctor'' (also known as ''Maggie'', 1958)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Troy|first=Una|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XLA_HaWQ-FAC&newbks=0&hl=en|title=Miss Maggie and the Doctor|date=1958|publisher=Dutton|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/06/29/110080354.html|title=Dr. Bill's Housekeeper|last=Cobb|first=Jane|date=29 June 1958|website=New York Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n* ''The Workhouse Graces'' (also known as ''The Graces of Ballykeen,'' 1959)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Minick|first=Elaine I.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662552/sisters-in-paupers-home-find-riches-in/|title=Sisters in Paupers' Home Find Riches in Friendship|date=1960-01-10|work=Chattanooga Daily Times|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=16|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* ''The Other End of the Bridge'' (1960)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Troy|first=Una|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XrJSxAEACAAJ&newbks=0&hl=en|title=The Other End of the Bridge|date=1960|publisher=Heinemann|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Johnson|first=C. W.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662718/irish-feuding-becomes-frolicc-w/|title=Irish Feuding Becomes Frolic|date=1961-01-08|work=Springfield Leader and Press|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=27|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* ''Esmond'' (1962)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burns|first=G. Frank|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662804/trigamyg-frank-burns/|title=Trigamy|date=1962-07-22|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=32|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* ''The Brimstone Halo'' (also known as ''The Prodigal Father'', 1965)<ref>{{Cite news|last=B. H. H.|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662647/prodigal-father-returns-to-family-he/|title='Prodigal Father' Returns to Family He Left Behind|date=1965-03-21|work=The Anniston Star|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|pages=16|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n* ''The Benefactors'' (1969)\n* ''The Castle Nobody Wanted'' (1970)\n* ''Tiger Puss'' (1970)\n* ''Doctor Go Home'' (1973)\n* ''Out of Everywhere'' (1976)\n* ''Caught in the Furze'' (1977)\n* ''A Sack of Gold'' (1979)\n* ''So True a Fool'' (1981)\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1931, Una Troy married Joseph C. Walsh of [[Bunmahon|Bonmahon]], who served as physician to the [[Irish Republican Army (1922\u20131969)|Irish Republican Army]] (IRA),<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Reilly|first=Terence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E-sl4wW6KwcC&pg=PA220&dq=%22Una+Troy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=R6rqTv7GIdSXhQeirbXBCA&ved=0CFAQ6AEwBzgU#v=onepage&q=%22Una%20Troy%22&f=false|title=Rebel Heart: George Lennon: Flying Column Commander|publisher=Mercier Press Ltd|year=2009|isbn=978-1-85635-649-7|pages=220|accessdate=2011-12-16}}</ref> and later as a coroner. Her sister-in-law May Walsh was married to Irish artist [[Se\u00e1n Keating]]. The couple lived in [[Clonmel]] for most of their lives together, and had a daughter, Janet (1932-2002). Una Troy was widowed when Dr. Walsh died in 1969, and she died in 1993 in Bonmahon, County Waterford.<ref name=\":1\" /> Many of her papers are in the collection of the [[National Library of Ireland]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.unatroy.info Una Troy], a website run by Troy biographer and archivist Ann M. Butler.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0873914}}\n*Claire Connolly, \"Scholarcast 19: Four Nations Feminism: Una Troy and [[Menna Gallie]]\", an audio program from [[University College Dublin]].\n*[https://www.rte.ie/archives/2017/0228/856053-times-changing-in-clonmel/ \"Clonmel at Crossroads of Change\"] (16 March 1967), an episode of the RT\u00c9 series ''Discovery,'' featuring Una Troy.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Troy, Una}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:People from County Cork]]\n[[Category:People from County Waterford]]\n[[Category:Irish women novelists]]\n[[Category:Irish women dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "name_user": "Smirkybec", "label": "safe", "comment": "adding link for May Keating", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Una_Troy"}
{"title_page": "Rodolfo Massi", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name        = Rodolfo Massi\n| image       =\n| full_name   = Rodolfo Massi\n| nickname    = Il Farmacista (the pharmacist)<ref name=\"nrc\"/>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1965|9|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Corinaldo]], [[Italy]]\n| currentteam = Retired\n| discipline  = [[Road bicycle racing|Road]]\n| role        = Rider\n| ridertype   =\n| proyears1   = 1987\n| proteam1    = Magniflex\n| proyears2   = 1988\n| proteam2    = Alba Cucine-Benotto\n| proyears3   = 1989\n| proteam3    = {{ct|ATA|1989}}\n| proyears4   = 1990&ndash;1991\n| proteam4    = Ariostea\n| proyears5   = 1992\n| proteam5    = Jolly Componibili-Club 88\n| proyears6   = 1993&ndash;1994\n| proteam6    = {{ct|AMO|1993}}\n| proyears7   = 1995&ndash;1996\n| proteam7    = {{ct|REF|1995}}\n| proyears8   = 1997&ndash;1998\n| proteam8    = {{ct|ALM|1997}}\n| proyears9   = 1999\n| proteam9    = [[Liquigas]]\n| proyears10  = 2000\n| proteam10   = {{ct|CTA|2000}}\n| proyears11  = 2001\n| proteam11   = Mobilvetta Design-Formaggi Trentini\n| proyears12  = 2002\n| proteam12   = {{ct|AMO|2002}}\n| proyears13  = 2003\n| proteam13   = {{ct|AND|2003}}\n| majorwins   = [[Giro d'Italia]], 1 stage<br>[[Tour de France]], 1 stage<br>[[Tour M\u00e9diterran\u00e9en]] (1998)\n}}\n\n'''Rodolfo Massi''' ({{IPA-it|ro\u02c8dolfo \u02c8massi}}; born 17 September 1965 in [[Corinaldo]]) is an [[Italy|Italian]] former professional [[road bicycle racer]]. He won a stage in [[1996 Giro d'Italia]] and [[1998 Tour de France]], but was expelled from the 1998 Tour de France after illegal doping was found in his hotel room. In the [[1990 Tour de France]], Massi was the [[Lanterne rouge]].\n\n==Biography==\nAs an amateur, Massi won many races, and when he became a professional cyclist in 1987, much was expected from him.<ref name=\"nrc\">{{cite web|url=http://retro.nrc.nl/W2/Lab/Tour/T76.html|date=31 July 1998|publisher=NRC|language=Dutch|title=Italiaan Massi de apotheker van het peloton}}</ref> In 1988, he broke a leg, and after the operation, one of his legs was a few centimeters shorter than the other. Massi often complained that he was not able to cycle in a regular way, and became a domestique for many different teams.<ref name=\"nrc\"/>\n\nIn 1998, he had his best year. He won the [[Tour M\u00e9diterran\u00e9en]] and the [[Giro di Calabria]].<ref name=\"nrc\"/> In the [[1998 Tour de France|Tour de France]], he won a mountain stage, and after the 16th stage was in seventh place in the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], and leading the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]], when corticoids were found in his hotel room.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bicycle.net/2008/ten-years-later-festina-doping-affair-still-not-forgotten|title=Ten Years Later, Festina Doping Affair Still Not Forgotten|date=3 July 2008|publisher=Bicycle|work=bicycle.net|author=Davis, Justin|accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref> He was questioned by the police, and was not able to start the next stage. Massi was the first rider in history to be arrested for breaking doping laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/archief_gratis/article769912.ece/Een_Tour_die_voortleeft_als_de_ronde_van_de_dopingschandalen|title=Een Tour die voortleeft als de ronde van de dopingschandalen|language=Dutch|publisher=Volkskrant|date=3 August 1998|accessdate=19 April 2010|author=Lieshout, Marcel van}}</ref> Later, all legal charges against him were dropped,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/988530.stm|title='Festina Affair': A timeline|publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 October 2000|accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref> but the Italian Olympic Committee banned him for six months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/nov98/nov4.shtml|title=Cycling News and Analysis|date=4 November 1998|work=Cyclingnews|accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\nSource:<ref>{{Cycling Archives|4882}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1994\n:[[Settimana internazionale di Coppi e Bartali]]\n;1996\n:[[1996 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n::Winner stage 10\n;1997\n:[[Tour du Haut Var]]\n:Stage 4, Vuelta Ciclista a la Communidad Valenciana\n;1998\n:[[Tour M\u00e9diterran\u00e9en]]\n:Stage 2, Giro di Calabria\n:Giro di Calabria\n:Stage 2, Crit\u00e9rium International\n:[[1998 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 10\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of doping cases in cycling]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.rodolfomassi.it/}} {{in lang|it}}\n*[http://histo.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/739.html Official Tour de France results for Rodolfo Massi]\n\n{{Tour de France Lanterne Rouge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Massi, Rodolfo}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Italian Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:Italian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in cycling]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Ancona]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Marche]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name        = Rodolfo Massi\n| image       =\n| full_name   = Rodolfo Massi\n| nickname    = Il Farmacista (the pharmacist)<ref name=\"nrc\"/>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1965|9|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Corinaldo]], [[Italy]]\n| currentteam = Retired\n| discipline  = [[Road bicycle racing|Road]]\n| role        = Rider\n| ridertype   =\n| proyears1   = 1987\n| proteam1    = Magniflex\n| proyears2   = 1988\n| proteam2    = Alba Cucine-Benotto\n| proyears3   = 1989\n| proteam3    = {{ct|ATA|1989}}\n| proyears4   = 1990&ndash;1991\n| proteam4    = Ariostea\n| proyears5   = 1992\n| proteam5    = Jolly Componibili-Club 88\n| proyears6   = 1993&ndash;1994\n| proteam6    = {{ct|AMO|1993}}\n| proyears7   = 1995&ndash;1996\n| proteam7    = {{ct|REF|1995}}\n| proyears8   = 1997&ndash;1998\n| proteam8    = {{ct|ALM|1997}}\n| proyears9   = 1999\n| proteam9    = [[Liquigas]]\n| proyears10  = 2000\n| proteam10   = {{ct|CTA|2000}}\n| proyears11  = 2001\n| proteam11   = Mobilvetta Design-Formaggi Trentini\n| proyears12  = 2002\n| proteam12   = {{ct|AMO|2002}}\n| proyears13  = 2003\n| proteam13   = {{ct|AND|2003}}\n| majorwins   = [[Giro d'Italia]], 1 stage<br>[[Tour de France]], 1 stage<br>[[Tour M\u00e9diterran\u00e9en]] (1998)\n}}\n\n'''Rodolfo Massi''' ({{IPA-it|ro\u02c8dolfo \u02c8massi}}; born 17 September 1965 in [[Corinaldo]]) is an [[Italy|Italian]] former professional [[road bicycle racer]]. He won a stage in [[1996 Giro d'Italia]] and [[1998 Tour de France]], but was expelled from the 1998 Tour de France after illegal doping was found in his hotel room. In the [[1990 Tour de France]], Massi was the [[Lanterne rouge]].\n\n==Biography==\nAs an amateur, Massi won many races, and when he became a professional cyclist in 1987, much was expected from him.<ref name=\"nrc\">{{cite web|url=http://retro.nrc.nl/W2/Lab/Tour/T76.html|date=31 July 1998|publisher=NRC|language=Dutch|title=Italiaan Massi de apotheker van het peloton}}</ref> In 1988, he broke a leg, and after the operation, one of his legs was a few centimeters shorter than the other. Massi often complained that he was not able to cycle in a regular way, and became a domestique for many different teams.<ref name=\"nrc\"/>\n\nIn 1998, he had his best year. He won the [[Tour M\u00e9diterran\u00e9en]] and the [[Giro di Calabria]].<ref name=\"nrc\"/> In the [[1998 Tour de France|Tour de France]], he won a mountain stage, and after the 16th stage was in seventh place in the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], and leading the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]], when corticoids were found in his hotel room.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bicycle.net/2008/ten-years-later-festina-doping-affair-still-not-forgotten|title=Ten Years Later, Festina Doping Affair Still Not Forgotten|date=3 July 2008|publisher=Bicycle|work=bicycle.net|author=Davis, Justin|accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref> He was questioned by the police, and was not able to start the next stage. Massi was the first rider in history to be arrested for breaking doping laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/archief_gratis/article769912.ece/Een_Tour_die_voortleeft_als_de_ronde_van_de_dopingschandalen|title=Een Tour die voortleeft als de ronde van de dopingschandalen|language=Dutch|publisher=Volkskrant|date=3 August 1998|accessdate=19 April 2010|author=Lieshout, Marcel van}}</ref> Later, all legal charges against him were dropped,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/988530.stm|title='Festina Affair': A timeline|publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 October 2000|accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref> but the Italian Olympic Committee banned him for six months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/nov98/nov4.shtml|title=Cycling News and Analysis|date=4 November 1998|work=Cyclingnews|accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\nSource:<ref>{{Cycling Archives|4882}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1994\n:[[Settimana internazionale di Coppi e Bartali]]\n;1996\n:[[1996 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n::Winner stage 10\n;1997\n:[[Tour du Haut Var]]\n:Stage 4, Vuelta Ciclista a la Communidad Valenciana\n;1998\n:[[Tour M\u00e9diterran\u00e9en]]\n:Stage 2, Giro di Calabria\n:Giro di Calabria\n:Stage 2, Crit\u00e9rium International\n:[[1998 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 10\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of doping cases in cycling]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.rodolfomassi.it/}} {{in lang|it}}\n*[http://histo.letour.